N2  - Introduction: Alzheimer’s disease (AD) is the most common form of Dementia accounting for over 60-70% cases. Various neuromodulation techniques are being studies for AD including transcranial magnetic stimulation, transcranial electrical stimulation, deep brain stimulation, ultrasound stimulation, photo-biomodulation, and visual or auditory stimulation. Our review focusses on transcranial electrical stimulation specifically the effects of transcranial direct current stimulation (tDCS) in AD patients. Materials / Methods: We utilized the Preferred Reporting Items for Systematic Reviews and Meta-Analyses (PRISMA) guidelines as a template for the methodology Systematic searches were conducted for relevant evidence using PubMed, Science Direct and Cochrane Library databases for Randomized clinical Trials. The following search was done using MeSH terms (Transcranial Direct Current Stimulation) AND (Alzheimer’s) in the ‘Title/Abstract’. After removing duplicates and screening through titles and abstracts, we assessed 50 full text articles,14 trials were included in our study. Results: 11 studies reported the effect on cognitive patients after tDCS and reported variable results including 6 reporting improvement after tDCS sessions and 4 reporting no significant change following tDCS. Working memory, recognition memory, guessing memory performances were improved whereas no affect was seen on associative and verbal memory. There was no significant change in any neuro-psychiatric symptom. No improvement was seen in attention tasks however one study reported an increase in performance IQ. Discussion: The effects of tDCS depended on the type (Anodal, Cathodal or mixed) and placement of electrodes. The most common area of placement of electrodes was dorsolateral prefrontal cortex followed by parietal and temporal cortex. Additional trainings such as Working memory training contributed to positive outcomes. Conclusions: tDCS may be beneficial for AD patients in terms of improving cognitive status (depending on type of tDCS), specific types of memory and IQ. Supplemental Data: [Formula presented] Learning Objectives: To explore the effect of Transcranial Direct-current Stimulation in Alzheimer's patients for the following domains: 1- Cognitive status 2- Memory functions 3- Neuropsychiatric functions And study factors affecting the outcomes of therapy. Keywords: Transcranial Direct Current Stimulation, Neurodegenerative disorders, Alzheimer's disease, neuromodulation
