N2  - Introduction: First successful extracorporeal shockwaves application in medicine was the non-invasive kidney stone disintegration in 1980. It took about 10 years to recognize that low intensity shockwaves have the ability to stimulate healing process in the body. Shockwaves proved to be efficient for the treatment of non-unions, tendon and muscular pain, delayed wound healing, heart insufficiency, erectile dysfunction and of other indications. The working principle is the mechanical stimulation of biological processes called mechanotransduction resulting in increased cell metabolism, release of nitric oxide and of numerous growth factors. There is also an anti-inflammatory effect, stimulation of stem cells and of the innate immune system. The key application in the neurology was the treatment of pain and spasm starting 1990. The pain treatment within the complete musculoskeletal system (trigger points) became very soon standard orthopedic procedure. Analgesic effect of the shockwaves is based mainly on reduction of substance P concentration and the reduction of the unmyelinated nerve endings. Materials / Methods: First patients with spinal cord injury have been treated in 2004. The next step was the treatment of patients with unresponsive wakefulness. A new term, Transcranial Extracorporeal Shockwave Treatment (TESWT) was introduced. In parallel, the scientific investigations of the shockwaves on the nervous system in general continued. It was shown that shockwaves not only stimulate, but also regenerate the nerves after lesions. The typical treatment protocol consists of 6 sessions in two weeks. During one session, 6000 shockwave pulses with Energy Flux Density of 0.20-0.25mJ/mm2 are applied. Results: Meanwhile there is an increasing experience with the treatment of the central nervous system. Patients with Parkinson’s and Alzheimer’s disease are treated experimentally since 2010. Typical improvement of the CERAD score is 10%. The term TPS (Transcranial Pulse Stimulation) has been introduced for shockwave stimulation of the brain. Discussion: The shockwave (TPS) treatment of the Alzheimer’s disease is meanwhile used by many medical centers. Placebo controlled trials for Alzheimer’s and Parkinson’s disease are ongoing. A large multicenter trial for shockwave treatment of acute spinal cord injuries started in 2021. Shockwaves, next to the stimulation, modulation and regeneration of brain can also open the Blood Brain Barrier. Conclusions: Shockwaves application is effective and safe. There have been no relevant negative side effect observed. Learning Objectives: 1. Shockwaves are successfully used in medicine since 1980 2. Low intensity shockwaves, ESWT are used for stimulation of the healing process 3. Stimulation of of biological processes by shockwaves is called mechanotransduction. Keyword: Shockwaves, Alzheimer's disease, brain, spine, TPS
