N2  - Introduction: Background: Cerebral small vessel disease (CSVD) is a condition of clinical and neuroimaging presentations that arise mainly from impairment of the cerebral small perforating vessels causing white matter hyperintensities, lacunes, cerebral microbleeds and insidiously progressive disturbance of gait, cognition and sphincteric control. Currently there is no consensus on a specific management for these symptoms. So we tried rTMS as a neuromodulation technique that might enhance brain plasticity and stimulate redundant circuitry and can modulated associated inflammatory process. Aim of work: Study the effect of high frequency rTMS on gait, cognitive and sphincteric symptoms, in addition to IL-1B levels among patients with incidental CSVD. Materials / Methods: 40 patients are included, with MRI documented incidental CSVD, and were equally randomized to active and sham groups. Active group received 6 sessions of 10hz, Cz stimulation at an intensity of 110% of resting motor threshold. Sham group received 6 sham sessions. Baseline line demographic data, vascular risk factors, radiological scales (Fazekas and Global cortical atrophy scale) were done to all patients. Baseline, post-sessions and 1 month follow up assessments were done for gait (10 Meter walk test (10MWT), Minibest (MB), Berg Balance test (BBT)), cognition ( FAB, Addenbrooke’s test) and Urinary symptoms ( ICIQ) and IL-1B Levels. Results: Active rTMS group showed statistically significant improvement of all motor, cognitive and sphincteric scales and decrease of IL-1B level (P ˂ 0.01). Discussion: Treatment of CSVD is challenging and these patients are prone to recurrent falls due to gait and cognitive impairment. Neuromodulation of brain connectivity can be a safe and promising technique, however our results need to be replicated on a large number of patients. Also the duration of efficacy needs to be evaluated in order to plan a treatment protocol for such patients. Conclusions: Our results suggest that high frequency rTMS sessions applied to Cz showed statistically significant improvement in gait, cognitive and urinary performance in patients with CSVD. Learning Objectives: 1- highlight the importance of identifying CSVD as a common incidental finding in elderly 2- identify the seriousness of gait and cognitive deficit in CSVD and the need to treat them 3- notify the possibility of using non invasive stimulation as a safe method to ameliorate symptoms of CSVD. Keyword: Small vessel disease, IL-1.
