N2  - Introduction: Alzheimer’s disease (AD) is typically characterized by memory loss, with brain structural and functional dysfunction involving not only the hippocampus but also the Default Mode Network (DMN), for which the Precuneus (PC) is a key node. Recently, our group showed that 20-Hz repetitive Transcranial Magnetic Stimulation (rTMS) over the PC increases long-term memory performance in AD, suggesting the PC as the ideal target for stimulation to slow down cognitive decline in AD. Here we propose a randomized double-blind clinical trial to determine the effects of rTMS applied over the PC on structural and functional connectivity in patients with mild-to-moderate AD. Methods: Fourteen patients were randomly assigned to treatment with rTMS (Real, n=7) or placebo (Sham, n=7). Both groups received an intensive 2-week course with daily rTMS sessions, followed by a maintenance phase in which rTMS has been applied once a week for 6 months. Each rTMS session consisted of forty, 2-second trains delivered at 20 Hz that were spaced out by 28 seconds, for a total of 1600 stimuli in 20 minutes. Before and after six months of treatment structural and functional MRIs have been collected on a Siemens PRISMA scanner with a 64-channel head-coil. Results: Voxel-based morphometry analysis showed Gray Matter (GM) loss in the PC six months after the treatment specifically for the Sham Group (p<0.001), while both groups showed GM loss in the bilateral superior temporal gyri (p<0.001). Moreover, the seed-to-voxel analysis considering as seed the PC revealed an increase in functional connectivity (FC) between PC and several nodes of DMN (p<0.05, FDR-corrected) over parietal and frontal areas after rTMS in the Real Group. Additionally, a decrease in FC between PC and parietal nodes belonging to the network negatively correlated to DMN has been also observed after rTMS in the Real Group. No significant results in the FC analysis have been found for the Sham Group. Conclusion: Even if preliminary, these results showing GM conservation and FC changes affecting both local and network-to-network connectivity dynamics in the Real Group triggers the possibility of using this non-invasive approach to increase brain plasticity in AD patients by manipulating distributed network connectivity patterns.
