N2  - Introduction: A deficient working memory (WM) is a cardinal symptom of aging and mild cognitive impairment (MCI) with a crucial impact on daily functioning. One of the presumed causes of such decline is altered frontoparietal (FPCN) network oscillations. In this pilot study, our primary aim was to test the efficacy of different multifocal transcranial alternative current stimulation (tACS) protocols to synchronize the FPCN theta oscillations — a frequency relevant to memory encoding. Secondly, numerous studies ascribed importance to the FPCN network as an important hub of cognitive reserve, compensating for other distinct cognitive domains. Methods: Four different montages of tACS were applied: frontal, parietal, and frontoparietal in phase and out of phase; in a randomized within-subject placebo-controlled (sham) design on 20 elderly subjects. Each stimulation targeted individualized coordinates of the medial frontal gyrus (MFG) and/or the inferior parietal lobule (IPL) based on individually processed data from a functional magnetic resonance (fMRI) session where subjects solved the same visual N-back task. Behavioral (N-back task during the stimulations) and resting-state (rs) fMRI connectivity differences (post-pre changes) were analyzed using repeated linear mixed models (LMM) with unstructured covariance type where stimulation type (montages) and N-back difficulty were predictors. Results: The LMM yielded a significant stimulation target*N-back difficulty effect on the behavioral performance (F(4,52.76) = 3.76, p <0.009) and a successive pairwise comparison of the stimulation targets suggested the greatest effect of the frontal montage. The frontal target was significantly better than the sham, in-phase, and out-of-phase (p <.05), but only numerically better than the parietal (p = 0.12). Resting-state analyses supported the superiority of the frontal montage (F(4,9.60) = 9.91, p = 0.002) which significantly decreased the connectivity between IPL and the FPCN in comparison to all other montages, and this correlated with improvement in the N-back task (r = -0.26, p <0.05). Conclusion: The results of our pilot study show that the frontal stimulation of the MFG is significantly superior to all other targets and placebo in improving WM performance. The stimulation led to brain plasticity changes within the frontoparietal network (resting-state connectivity decreases) which were associated with the observed WM improvement. Previous studies have already pointed out that the mechanism of the tACS network modulation may be different from the direct (tDCS) stimulation, which usually leads to increased connectivity, and the tACS seems to promote network efficiency and focusing effects.
