N2  - Introduction: Preserved cognitive functions can dramatically improve the quality of life in old age. On the other hand, cognitive impairment that exceeds healthy aging levels can lead to depression, anxiety and apathy. The fact that the prevalence of cognitive disorders such as mild cognitive impairment (MCI) or Alzheimer’s disease (AD) is expected to increase dramatically in the coming years due to demographic changes demonstrates the increasing importance of appropriate treatment options. Two methods that can potentially improve cognitive functions are noninvasive brain stimulation (NBS) and cognitive training. Methods: We used transcranial alternating current stimulation (tACS) as a subtype of NBS techniques to stimulate the dorsolateral prefrontal cortex (DLPFC) bilaterally at F3/F4, applying the novel theta-gamma cross frequency coupling (CFC) protocol. Cognitive training was performed during stimulation (20 min) and was based on n-back tasks to target working memory. Subjects were randomly assigned to a real or sham group and were stimulated in 16 sessions over a 6-week period. In order to determine direct effects as well as long-term (LT) effects we conducted three cognitive assessments (before treatment, after treatment and three months after treatment). The cognitive tests included the Montreal Cognitive Assessment (MoCA), the Paired Associate Learning (PAL) task, the Rey’s Auditory Verbal Learning (RAVL) task, the Attention Network Task (ANT), the story recall task (CRAFT 21), the block tapping task (CORSI) and the Trail Making Test (TMT). Our primary focus is the PAL task, which measures declarative memory skills. At this stage we included eighty participants aged 55-85 with either cognitive functions on a healthy aging level or (mild) cognitive impairment based on the individual MoCA score. Results: Based on the literature we hypothesized that active theta-gamma tACS stimulation of the DLPFC would positively affect cognitive functions in the elderly, expecting a larger effect in already cognitively impaired individuals. Conclusion: Status of the work: In the phase of data collection and analysis. Additional authors might be included after this process, in the final version.
