N2  - Introduction: Visual cognition deficits are one of the key symptoms of mild cognitive impairment (MCI). We demonstrated previously that aberrant brain activity associated with object identification from differing viewpoints might be a good predictor of neurodegeneration in AD and PD. Furthermore, it is well established that visual processing engages top-down frontoparietal networks, including the DLPFC, in addition to visual pathways. We previously demonstrated that left-DLPFC tDCS had a positive immediate effect on visual working memory in an elderly population. The primary goal of this randomized controlled trial was to see if the intensified transcranial direct current stimulation protocol could improve visual cognition in MCI patients both immediately and long-term. Second, we sought to comprehend the resting-state and global network changes related to tDCS-induced enhancement. Methods: For five days in a row, intensified anodal tDCS was applied over the left DLPFC with the cathode placed over the contralateral orbitofrontal cortex using 2mA of current in two 20-minute trains separated by a 20-minute pause on 32 subjects (14 real and 16 sham group). Participants performed visual working memory during tDCS. Behavioral (VOMT post-pre, 1-month post-pre) and fMRI connectivity, as well as changes in graph theory metrics, were analyzed using paired and independent t-tests, along with repeated linear mixed models with unstructured covariance type and stimulation type as factors. Results: The independent sample t-test indicates that there are no statistically significant short-term (t(33) =−1,707, p =0.09) or long-term (t(35) =−0.482, p =0.63) effects of tDCS on behavioral performance. However, we found improvements in the real tDCS group immediately after the end of the stimulation regimen compared to baseline (t(14) =−2.043, p.05), but not in the sham group (t(16) =.948,p =0.52). While acute behavioral improvement in VOMT was correlated with changes in visual network modularity (r = 0.451, p = 0.05), only the stimulation type factor was significant (F(1,62.455), p =0.013), but not the stim type*time (F(1,62.455), p =0.18). Conclusion: Our results indicate that intensified tDCS could enhance the visual cognition in MCI patients immediately following the end of the regimen. However, based on our findings, the effects are only modulatory, and thus no LTP-like long-term effects were observed. Previous research suggests that the timing of the stimulation trains/sessions could influence the long-term LTP-like plasticity effects, which warrants further investigation.
