N2  - Objectives: Sometimes, resective surgery is not appropriate to treat focal perceptive aware seizures due to the high risk of severe morbidity. In these cases, neuromodulation may be preferable. Anterior thalamus DBS is not infrequently unsuccessful to control these types of seizures. Considering all that, we have started a prospective open study to determine the efficacy of DBS of specific thalamic nuclei to control focal aware seizures. This study was approved by the National Research Ethics Committee. We report the first case of this series, a patient with focal visual epilepsy submitted to DBS of the lateral geniculate body (LGB). Methods: Case report: 60- year-old female patient, presenting focal seizures since age 8, manifesting as a white cloud in the left visual field and evolving with disperceptive manifestations, including automatism of the left hand. She presented a mean of 10 episodes/day. Medications: lamotrigine 200mg BID, levetiracetam 1125mg BID, and clobazam 10mg SID. MR was unremarkable. Interictal PET-CT showed hypometabolism on the right occipital lobe. Video-EEG demonstrated epileptogenic activity starting on the right occipital lobe, spreading to the ipsilateral anterior temporal lobe. Neuropsychological evaluation disclosed diffuse cognitive impairment. We elected right stereotactic LGB-DBS to treat this patient. Intraoperatively, confirmation of the target margins was performed using MER under photic stimulation and macrostimulation. The contact 1 of the 3389 lead was placed in the physiological center of the target. Results: There were no surgical complications. Postoperative MR confirmed adequate position of the electrode. The best parameters of stimulation determined along a 10-month trial were 2-0+/300μs/130Hz/3V continuous stimulation. Seizure frequency was decreased by 90%. Postoperative PET-CT showed accentuation of the preoperative hypometabolism on the right occipital lobe. Postoperative neuropsychological evaluation revealed improvement in verbal memory and naming. SF-36 demonstrated significant improvement in all domains, except for emotional limitations, and GAF improved by 20 points. Postoperative interictal EEGs and campimetry were unremarkable. Medications were kept unchanged during the 10-month follow-up. Conclusions: This is the first time specific thalamic nuclei DBS (LGB) was performed to treat focal seizures. The 90% seizure reduction suggests that this technique may be a promising tool for the treatment of this type of epilepsy.
