N2  - Introduction: The concept of a Neuromodulation Committee was created to enact a collaborative and interdisciplinary approach to neuromodulation. The process has been implemented at the University of California, Davis (UCD) and Stanford University. The committee is composed of implanters, a pain psychologist who completes all pre-procedural psychological assessments, a nurse practitioner or physician assistant who sees patients for preoperative history and physicals, and current pain fellows. The goals of the committee are to weigh the risks and benefits of the neuromodulation device, approach, and patient candidacy. Fellows work closely with the attendings to help prepare patient cases for the committee. The case is presented in conjunction with pain psychologist input to determine the appropriateness for neuromodulation, and a consensus is obtained prior to proceeding. Methods: IRB approval was obtained for this retrospective study. Inclusion criteria were adult patients (age ≥ 18 years old) who underwent evaluation by the Neuromodulation Committee. Patients with insufficient data were excluded from the study. Retrospective chart review was completed on a total of 385 patients committee conferences at the UCD and Stanford University. Data collected from chart review included demographics (age, gender, race, ethnicity, height, weight, BMI), committee meeting results (proceed with trial), implant device/date, and explant date (if applicable). Results: Our teams recommended to proceed with an implantable device in 337 patients (88%) while for the remaining 48 patients, other conservative therapy was recommended before reconsideration. 23 patients (6%) had untreated psychiatric disorders, and they were referred for additional mental health follow-up. For 13 patients (3%), our teams decided that implantable devices would not be the best medical option because of the pain type (e.g. fibromyalgia, mechanical pain from fracture), pain spread (e.g. whole body pain), or significant other comorbidities. 5 patients had significant non-compliance or aggressive behavior in the past. 4 patients had instrumentation (that obliterated epidural space) or significant spinal canal stenosis at the target level of lead placement; we referred these patients for neurosurgical evaluation. 3 patients had significant cognitive impairment and did not have enough support at home to apprehend and maintain a neuromodulation therapy; we recommended continuing multidisciplinary conservative treatment. Our team recommended bariatric surgery consultation for weight loss with 2 patients. Conclusion: The Neurmodulation Committee aims to identify optimal patients for neuromodulation, avoid procedural challenges, decrease adverse events, and improve outcomes. More study is needed to examine the long term implications of this collaborative, multidisiplinary process. Disclosure: Scott Pritzlaff, MD: SPR Therapeutics: Consulting Fee: Self, Nalu Medical: Consulting Fee: Self, EBT medical: Consulting Fee:, Michael Leong, MD: Sorrento Therapeutics: Consulting Fee: Self, Vertos Medical: Consulting Fee: Self, Wex Pharmaceuticals: Contracted Research: Self, Vafi Salmasi, MD: None, Juliann Cho, MD: None, Micahael Jung, MD: None, Ravi Prasad, PhD: Bicycle Health: Ownership Interest:
