N2  - Objective: To assess efficacy and safety of DTBZ in patients with HD chorea in the three-year, open-label extension (OLE) study (ARC HD), including a post hoc safety analysis in patients receiving doses ≤48 and > 48 mg/d. Background: DTBZ is FDA-approved for the treatment of chorea in HD. In the pivotal First-HD trial, DTBZ treatment (up to 48 mg/d) reduced the Unified Huntington's Disease Rating Scale (UHDRS) total maximal chorea (TMC) score versus placebo over 12 weeks. In the long-term OLE study (ARC-HD), efficacy and safety of DTBZ were evaluated, with doses ranging from 6 to 72 mg/d. Methods: Patients who completed First-HD (Rollover) and patients who converted overnight from a stable dose of tetrabenazine (Switch) were included in ARC-HD. Doses were increased by 6 mg/d per week in a response-driven manner up to 48 mg/d (Week 8). Further increases were permitted by 12 mg/d per week up to 72 mg/d. A post-titration time point of 8 weeks was used for efficacy analyses. Safety was assessed over the entire treatment period; exposure-adjusted incidence rates (EAIRs; adverse events [AEs] per person-year) were calculated. EAIRs for selected AEs were evaluated in a post hoc analysis of patients receiving doses ≤48 and > 48 mg/d during the stable dose period. Results: Of 119 patients (Rollover, n = 82; Switch, n = 37), 81 (68%) completed long-term follow-up and 100 (84%) completed ≥1 year of treatment. Mean ± SD changes from baseline to Wk 8 in the Rollover and Switch cohorts, respectively, were - 4.5 ± 3.1 and - 2.1 ± 3.3 for total maximal chorea (TMC) score and - 7.1 ± 7.3 and - 2.4 ± 8.7 for total motor score (TMS). Mean ± SD changes from Wk 8 to Wk 145 were - 0.5 ± 5.2 for TMC and 8.2 ± 11.9 for TMS in the total population. DTBZ was generally well tolerated in both cohorts (Table). Common AEs (≥4% either cohort) included somnolence (Rollover, 20%; Switch, 30%), depression (32%; 22%), anxiety (27%; 35%), insomnia (23%; 16%), and akathisia (6%; 11%). A total of 49 patients were ever exposed to doses >48 mg/d; there were no differences in EAIRs for patients receiving doses ≤48 mg/d or > 48 mg/d. Conclusion: AEs observed with long-term DTBZ exposure in patients with HD chorea were consistent with First-HD. Efficacy in reducing chorea persisted over time. Some HD patients may benefit from doses >48 mg/d to control chorea, which were tolerated without increased EAIRs for selected AEs.
