N2  - Introduction/Purpose: The swallowing motor system and specifically its cortical substrates appear to have certain unique properties that make it highly susceptible to brain plasticity, both driven and following injury. Furthermore, neurogenic dysphagia is a common complication of brain disease, associated with poor outcomes, and yet treatment options remain limited. Therefore, translating the physiologic studies of areas such as neurostimulation into clinical populations becomes imperative. Methods: By applying a variety of neurophysiological and neuromodulatory techniques (described below), I will delve into the therapeutic application of neuroplasticity in the human swallowing motor system by initially examine the role of peripheral stimulation in modulating the cortical swallowing system. I will focus on inputs that target the pharynx, describe how these inputs alter cortical excitability, and then highlight clinical trial evidence to support their application in dysphagia after sub-acute and chronic stroke. Thereafter I will explore the application of non-invasive brain stimulation (NIBS) which has previously been used to treat nervous system disorders such as depression, pain modulation and cognitive impairment. Results: Peripheral stimulation in the form of pharyngeal electrical stimulation has been investigated over the last 20 years, ranging from phase I to phase III trials determining mechanism, dose response and therapeutic application in neurological dysphagia mainly in stroke patients. The results of these studies have shown that there is plausible promise, particularly in increasing rates of decannulation in tracheotomized stroke victims. Transcranial brain stimulation, in particular transcranial magnetic stimulation (TMS) and transcranial direct current stimulation (tDCS), together grouped under the term non-invasive brain stimulation (NIBS) have been utilized by a number of investigators for rehabilitation in early stage clinical trials, including dysphagia after neurological disease. Specifically, repetitive TMS (rTMS) and tDCS have been employed to promote improvements in function - via harnessing the principles of neuroplasticity. These studies, again mainly in dysphagic stroke, have indicated that both affected and unaffected hemispheric targeting appear to have merit, however there may be evidence that applying NIBS unaffected/ undamaged pathways promote greater improvements in swallowing function, when using higher intensities or higher frequencies. Discussion: Newer approaches to neurogenic oropharyngeal dysphagia are now emerging, and there is increasing interest in the role of neuromodulation to rehabilitate swallowing dysfunction in brain related disorders. Larger trials of these approaches are necessary to further strengthen the evidence base, but there is plausible promise that neuromodulation is likely to bring benefit to this significantly disabled population.
