N2  - Abstract The goal of this talk is twofold. First we aim to address enduring safety concerns regarding accelerated rTMS, particularly in the case of vulnerable neurological patients. Second we aim to address the dose-response curve for improving cognitive performance with rTMS. Toward the first goal, we will present findings from post-stroke patients with vascular cognitive impairment (VCI; N=14) and patients with amnestic mild cognitive impairment (MCI; N=14). We administered accelerated rTMS (intermittent theta burst) to left dorsolateral prefrontal cortex (dlPFC) delivered in runs of 600 pulses, eight times/day for three days. Participants completed at pre- and post-treatment in-depth neuroradiological characterization and safety assessment with flair, diffusion, susceptibility, angiography, perfusion gradient and volumetric imaging as well as neuropsychological assessment. No adverse events occurred as indexed in neuroradiological, neuropsychological or subjective side effects. This is the first comprehensive neuroradiological and neuropsychological examination of the safety of accelerated rTMS in VCI and MCI, or any condition. Toward the second goal, we will present findings from a study of the near-continuous dose response curve for accelerated rTMS toward improving intact cognition. We implemented a range of doses, including doses far exceeding those typically applied within healthy samples. Forty healthy participants were randomized to ten doses of accelerated rTMS to left dlPFC ranging from one to 10 active intermittent theta burst rTMS sessions/day for five days (600 pulses/session, total pulses 3,000 – 30,000). Pre- and post-rTMS participants completed neuropsychological assessment, structural MRI, and EEG. While dose-response results are blinded until the last four of the 40 participants complete participation this month, results will be presented for the dose-response curve for cognitive performance and EEG. We will additionally present the interim findings from an ongoing dose-response study of rTMS for mood and cognitive impairment in depression and anxiety. Keywords: stroke, MCI, TMS, safety
