N2  - Objective To investigate the effects of electroacupuncture combined with transcranial magnetic stimulation on learning-memory ability in rats with vascular dementia ( VaD) , and possible mechanisms. Methods A total of 48 healthy male Sprague-Dawley ( SD) rats, 240 -280 g, eight weeks, were randomly divided into four groups: sham-operated group (group S) , model group (group M) , electroacupuncture group (group E) and electroacupuncture + magnetic stimulation group (group EM), with 12 rates in each group. The VaD model was constructed by four-vessel occlusion method. DU20 (BaiHui) and DU14 (DaZhui) in the electroacupuncture group were acupunctured 30 min/time and 1 time/d for 14 consecutive days in group E. The rats in the group EM received transcranial magnetic stimulation after elcctroacupuncture intervention, 100magnetic pulses/time and 1 time/d for 14 consecutive days. The rats in the S group and the M group were fixed in the same manner and at the same time in the softness holder without giving other interventions. The learning-memory ability in rats was detected by Morris water maze test. The neuronal apoptosis in hippocampal CA1 region of rats was detected by terminal deoxynucleotidyl transferase-mediated 2'-deoxyuridine 5'-triphosphate nick-end labeling (TUNEL) assay. Western blot method was used to detect the relative content of phosphatidylinositol 3-kinase (PI3K), protein kinase B (Akt), phospho-Akt (p-Akt), mammalian target of rapamycin (mTOR) and phospho- mTOR(p-mTOR) proteins in hippocampus, and the ratio of p-Akt/Akt and the ratio of p-mTOR/mTOR were calculated. Results Comparing the group M, group E and group EM with the group S, the escape latency time ( [48.9 ±2.2] s, [40.8 ±2.2] s and [36.7 ±2.4] s vs. [33.6 ± 1.6] s ) and the first crossing time ([54. 8 ± 1. 8] s, [37. 8 ±2. 2] s and [30.2 ± 1.8] s w. [24.5 ± 1.8] s) were obviously extended (all P <0.05) , while the numbers of crossing the original platform within 2 minutes ( [3.2 ±0. 8 ] , [5. 6 ± 0. 8] and [7.6 ± 1.0] vs. [ 10.2 ±0. 8] ) were obviously decreased (all P <0.05); the neuronal apoptosis indexes in the hippocampal CA1 regions of rats were obviously increased (all P <0. 05) ; the relative content of P13K proteins in the hippocampus tissues of rats were significantly increased (all P < 0. 05), while the ratio of p-Akt/Akt and the ratio of p-mTOR/mTOR were significantly decreased (all P <0.05). Comparing the group E and group EM with the group M, the escape latency time and the first crossing time were obviously decreased (all P <0.05), while the numbers of crossing the original platform within 2 minutes were obviously increased (all P <0.05); the neuronal apoptosis index in hippocainpal CA1 regions of rats were significantly decreased (all P <0. 05) ; the relative content of PI3K proteins in hippocampus tissues of rats were significantly decreased (all P <0. 05) , while the ratio of p-Akt/Akt and the ratio of p-mTOR/ mTOR were significantly increased (all P <0.05). Comparing the group EM with the group E, the escape latency time and the first crossing time were significantly decreased (all P < 0. 05), while the number of crossing the original platform within 2 minutes were significantly increased ( P < 0. 05 ) ; the neuronal apoptosis index was significantly decreased (/><0.05) ; the relative content of PI3K protein was significantly decreased ( P < 0. 05 ) , while the ratio of p-Akt/Akt and the ratio of p-mTOR/mTOR were significantly increased (all /J<0.05). Conclusions Electroacupuncture combined with transcranial magnetic stimulation can improve spatial learning-memory ability of VaD rats and have better effect than using electroacupuncture alone. The mechanisms may be related to the activation of PI3K/Akt/mTOR signaling pathway and inhibition hippocampal neuronal apoptosis.
