N2  - Background: Alzheimer’s Disease (AD) is characterized by cognitive and neuropsychiatric symptoms (NPS). Some studies have shown abnormal cortical excitability in AD; however, findings have been inconsistent. Further, relationship between cortical excitability and clinical symptoms of AD is not clear. This systematic review and meta-analysis assessed evidence for abnormal cortical excitability and its relationship with clinical symptoms in AD. Methods: Search included EMBASE, MEDLINE, and PsychINFO databases to identify publications that quantitatively assessed cortical excitability or its relationship with clinical symptoms in AD. Effect sizes and 95% confidence intervals (CI) were calculated using Hedges’ g and metanalyses were conducted using random effects model. Results: We identified 895 publications out of which 60 were reviewed in full-text and 29 were included in the final review. Twenty-three studies reported on transcranial magnetic stimulation (TMS) motor threshold (rMT) were included in the meta-analyses. Compared with controls, the AD group showed reduced rMT (SMD = -0.82, 95% CI [-1.11, -0.52], p < 0.00001). There was evidence for an inverse association between cortical excitability and global cognition, but the literature was not sufficient to conduct a meta-analysis. Findings from studies using TMS combined with electroencephalography (EEG) were inconsistent. No publications reported on the relationship between cortical excitability and NPS. Conclusions: There is strong evidence of increased motor cortex excitability in AD. There is also some evidence of an inverse association between cortical excitability and cognition in AD. Future studies should assess cortical excitability directly using TMS combined with EEG and examine its relationship with cognition and NPS. Supported By: Centre for Addiction and Mental Health; University of Toronto Keywords: Cortical Excitability, Cognition, Neuropsychiatric symptoms
